  abstract = {The most metal-deficient stars hold important clues about the early buildup and chemical evolution of the Milky Way, and carbon-enhanced metal-poor (CEMP) stars are of special interest. However, little is known about CEMP stars in the Galactic bulge. In this paper, we use the large spectroscopic sample of metal-poor stars from the Pristine Inner Galaxy Survey (PIGS) to identify CEMP stars (\$\textbackslash rm \textbraceleft [C/Fe]\textbraceright{} \textbackslash geqslant +0.7\$) in the bulge region and to derive a CEMP fraction. We identify 96 new CEMP stars in the inner Galaxy, of which 62 are very metal-poor (\$\textbackslash rm \textbraceleft [Fe/H]\textbraceright{} \textbackslash lt -2.0\$); this is more than a 10-fold increase compared to the seven previously known bulge CEMP stars. The cumulative fraction of CEMP stars in PIGS is \$42\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash, +14\textbackslash, \textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash, -13\textbraceright{} \textbraceleft\textbraceleft\textbackslash{} \textbackslash rm per\textbackslash{} cent\textbraceright\textbraceright\$ for stars with \$\textbackslash rm \textbraceleft [Fe/H]\textbraceright{} \textbackslash lt -3.0\$, and decreases to \$16\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash, +3\textbackslash, \textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash, -3\textbraceright{} \textbraceleft\textbraceleft\textbackslash{} \textbackslash rm per\textbackslash{} cent\textbraceright\textbraceright\$ for \$\textbackslash rm \textbraceleft [Fe/H]\textbraceright{} \textbackslash lt -2.5\$ and \$5.7\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash, +0.6\textbackslash, \textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash, -0.5\textbraceright{} \textbraceleft\textbraceleft\textbackslash{} \textbackslash rm per\textbackslash{} cent\textbraceright\textbraceright\$ for \$\textbackslash rm \textbraceleft [Fe/H]\textbraceright{} \textbackslash lt -2.0\$. The PIGS inner Galaxy CEMP fraction for \$\textbackslash rm \textbraceleft [Fe/H]\textbraceright{} \textbackslash lt -3.0\$ is consistent with the halo fraction found in the literature, but at higher metallicities, the PIGS fraction is substantially lower. While this can partly be attributed to a photometric selection bias, such bias is unlikely to fully explain the low CEMP fraction at higher metallicities. Considering the typical carbon excesses and metallicity ranges for halo CEMP-s and CEMP-no stars, our results point to a possible deficiency of both CEMP-s and CEMP-no stars (especially the more metal-rich) in the inner Galaxy. The former is potentially related to a difference in the binary fraction, whereas the latter may be the result of a fast chemical enrichment in the early building blocks of the inner Galaxy.},
  langid = {english},
  file = {/Users/daniel/Zotero/storage/MQ29J56L/Arentsen et al. - 2021 - The pristine inner galaxy survey (PIGS) III carbon-enhanced metal-poor stars in the bulge.pdf}
}
