  doi = {10.1093/mnras/staf690},
  url = {https://doi.org/10.1093/mnras/staf690},
  urldate = {2026-01-30},
  abstract = {Nearby extremely metal-poor galaxies (XMPs) allow us to study primitive galaxy formation and evolution in greater detail than is possible at high redshift. This work promotes the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to efficiently search for XMPs in multiband imaging data based on their predicted N2 index (N2\,\$\textbackslash equiv \textbackslash log\$\textbraceleft\$[\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft N\textbraceright\textbackslash, \textbraceleft\textbraceleft\textbackslash small II\textbraceright\textbraceright ]\textbackslash, \textbackslash lambda 6585\$/H\,\$\textbackslash alpha\$\textbraceright ). We developed a sequential characterization pipeline, composed of three CNN procedures: (i) a classifier for metal-poor galaxies, (ii) a classifier for XMPs, and (iii) an N2 predictor. The pipeline is applied to over 7.7\,million Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS) DR17 imaging data without SDSS spectroscopy. The predicted N2 values are used to select promising candidates for observations. This approach was validated by new observations of 45 candidates with redshifts less than 0.065 using the 2.54\,m Isaac Newton Telescope and the 4.1\,m Southern Astrophysical Research Telescope between 2023 and 2024. All 45 candidates are confirmed to be metal poor, including 28 new discoveries. There are 18/45 galaxies lacking detectable \$[\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft N\textbraceright\textbackslash, \textbraceleft\textbraceleft\textbackslash small II\textbraceright\textbraceright ]\textbackslash, \textbackslash lambda 6585\$ lines (\$\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft{} S/N\textbraceright\&lt; 2\$); for these, we report \$2\textbackslash sigma\$ upper limits on their oxygen abundance. Our XMPs have estimated oxygen abundances of \$7.1\textbackslash le\$\$12+\textbackslash log \textbackslash left(\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft O/H\textbraceright{} \textbackslash right)\$\$\textbackslash le 8.7\$ (\$2\textbackslash sigma\$ upper limit), based on the N2 index, and 21 of them with estimated metallicity \$\&lt; 0.1\textbackslash,\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft{} Z\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot \textbraceright\$. Additionally, we identified 4 potential candidates of low-metallicity AGNs at \$\textbraceleft\textbackslash lesssim\textbraceright{} 0.1\textbackslash,\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft{} Z\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot \textbraceright\$. Finally, we found that our observed samples are mostly brighter in the g band compared to other filters, similar to blueberry galaxies, resembling green pea galaxies and high-redshift Ly\,\$\textbackslash alpha\$ emitters.},
  langid = {english},
