  urldate = {2024-12-10},
  abstract = {After a short introduction summarizing the observational data on chemical abundances in different astrophysical sites, the theoretical framework of chemical evolution is presented followed by a brief discussion on the current ideas on the initial mass function and star formation rate. Furthermore, a short review on the evolution of stars all over the range of masses is given, pointing out novelties as well uncertainties given by including in stellar models phenomena such as mass loss by stellar wind, semiconvection and convective overshooting. In addition to this, we discusss the stellar sites of production and ejection of several important elemental species and derive the bulk yields of chemical elements per stellar generation. Chemical models applying to the solar vicinity and galactic disk are given. In particular, we discuss the history of C, N, O and Fe in the galactic disk and current models for the evolution of disk galaxies in general. Finally, we address the attention to the chemical models for dwarf galaxies that are known to suffer from intense episodes of star formation.},
