  abstract = {Context. R Coronae Borealis (RCB) variables and their non-variable counterparts, the dustless Hydrogen-deficient Carbon (dLHdC) stars have been known to exhibit enhanced s-processed material on their surfaces, especially Sr, Y, and Ba. No comprehensive work has been done to explore the s-process in these types of stars, however one particular RCB star, U Aqr, has been under scrutiny for its extraordinary Sr enhancement. Aims: We aim to identify RCB and dLHdC stars that have significantly enhanced Sr abundances, such as U Aqr, and use stellar evolution models to begin to estimate the type of neutron exposure that occurs in a typical HdC star. Methods: We compared the strength of the Sr II 4077 \AA{} spectral line to Ca II H to identify the new subclass of Sr-rich HdCs. We additionally used the structural and abundance information from existing RCB MESA models to calculate the neutron exposure parameter, {$\tau$}. Results: We identified six stars in the Sr-rich class. Two are RCBs, and four are dLHdCs. We additionally found that the preferred RCB MESA model has a neutron exposure {$\tau$} {$\simeq$} 0.1 mb-1, which is lower than the estimated {$\tau$} between 0.15 and 0.6 mb-1 for the Sr-rich star U Aqr found in the literature. We found trends in the neutron exposure corresponding to He-burning shell temperature, metallicity, and assumed s-processing site. Conclusions: We have found a sub-class of six HdCs known as the Sr-rich class, which tend to lie in the halo, outside the typical distribution of RCBs and dLHdCs. We found that dLHdC stars are more likely to be Sr-rich than RCBs, with an occurrence rate of \textasciitilde 13\% for dLHdCs and \textasciitilde 2\% for RCBs. This is one of the first potential spectroscopic differences between RCBs and dLHdCs, along with dLHdCs having stronger surface abundances of 18O. We additionally found neutron exposure trends in our RCB models that will aide in understanding the interplay between model parameters and surface s-process elements. A table of pseudo-EWs is only available at the CDS via anonymous ftp to cdsarc.cds.unistra.fr (ftp://130.79.128.5) or via https://cdsarc.cds.unistra.fr/viz-bin/cat/J/A+A/667/A85},
  keywords = {Astrophysics - Solar and Stellar Astrophysics,methods: observational,stars: abundances,stars: carbon,stars: chemically peculiar,stars: evolution,supergiants},
  annotation = {ADS Bibcode: 2022A\&A...667A..85C},
  file = {/Users/daniel/Zotero/storage/YER2GHYH/Crawford et al. - 2022 - Peculiar hydrogen-deficient carbon stars strontiu.pdf}
}
