  urldate = {2025-05-28},
  abstract = {We present uniformly measured resolved stellar photometry and star formation histories (SFHs) for 36 nearby (\$\textbackslash lesssim\$ 400 kpc) ultra-faint dwarf galaxies (UFDs; \$-7.1 \textbackslash le M\_V \textbackslash le +0.0\$) from new and archival HST imaging. We measure homogeneous distances to all systems via isochrone fitting and find good agreement (\$\textbackslash le\$ 2\%) for the 18 UFDs that have literature RR Lyrae distances. From the ensemble of SFHs, we find: (i) an average quenching time (here defined as the lookback time by which 80\% of the stellar mass formed, \${$\tau\_$}\textbraceleft 80\textbraceright\$) of 12.48 \$\textbackslash pm\$ 0.18 Gyr ago (\$z = 4.6\_\textbraceleft -0.5\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.6\textbraceright\$), which is compatible with reionization-based quenching scenarios; and (ii) modest evidence of a delay (\$\textbackslash lesssim\$ 800 Myr) in quenching times of UFDs thought to be satellites of the LMC or on their first infall, relative to long-term Galactic satellites, which is consistent with previous findings. We show that robust SFH measurement via the ancient main sequence turnoff (MSTO) requires a minimum effective luminosity (i.e., luminosity within the observed field of view) of \$M\_V \textbackslash leq -2.5\$, which corresponds to \$\textbackslash sim\$100 stars around the MSTO. We also find that increasing the S/N above \$\textbackslash sim\$100 at the MSTO does not improve SFH precision, which remains dominated by stochastic effects associated with the number of available stars. A main challenge driving the precision of UFD SFHs is limitations in the accuracy of foreground dust maps. We make all photometry catalogs public as the first data release of a larger HST archival program targeting all dwarf galaxies within \$\textbackslash sim\$1.3 Mpc.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {Astrophysics of Galaxies,to read},
  annotation = {ADS Bibcode: 2025arXiv250518252D},
  file = {/Users/daniel/Zotero/storage/BRF478LU/Durbin et al. - 2025 - The HST Legacy Archival Uniform Reduction of Local Group Imaging (LAURELIN). I. Photometry and Star.pdf}
