  url = {https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2022MNRAS.516.3944M},
  urldate = {2025-04-30},
  abstract = {We use GRUMPY, a simple regulator-type model for dwarf galaxy formation and evolution, to forward model the dwarf galaxy satellite population of the Milky Way (MW) using the Caterpillar zoom-in simulation suite. We show that luminosity and distance distributions of the model satellites are consistent with the distributions measured in the DES, PS1, and SDSS surveys, even without including a model for the orphan galaxies. We also show that our model for dwarf galaxy sizes can simultaneously reproduce the observed distribution of stellar half-mass radii, r1/2, of the MW satellites and the overall r1/2-M{$\star$} relation exhibited by observed dwarf galaxies. The model predicts that some of the observed faint stellar systems with r1/2 {$<$} 10 pc are ultra-faint dwarf galaxies. Scaling of the stellar mass M{$\star$} and peak halo mass Mpeak for the model satellites is not described by a power law, but has a clear flattening of M{$\star$}-Mpeak scaling at \$M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm peak\textbraceright{} 10\textasciicircum 8\textbackslash, \textbackslash, M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot \textbraceright\$ imprinted by reionization. As a result, the fraction of low mass haloes (\$M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm peak\textbraceright{} 10\textasciicircum 8 \textbackslash, M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot \textbraceright\$) hosting galaxies with MV {$<$} 0 is predicted to be 50 per cent at \$M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm peak\textbraceright\textbackslash sim 3.6 \textbackslash times 10\textasciicircum 7\textbackslash, \textbackslash, M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot \textbraceright\$. We find that such high fraction at that halo mass helps to reproduce the number of dwarf galaxies discovered recently in the HSC-SSP survey. Using the model we forecast that there should be the total of \$440\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +201\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -147\textbraceright\$ (68 per cent confidence interval) MW satellites with MV {$<$} 0 and r1/2 {$>$} 10 pc within 300 kpc and make specific predictions for the HSC-SSP, DELVE-WIDE, and LSST surveys.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {Astrophysics - Astrophysics of Galaxies,galaxies: dwarf,galaxies: haloes,galaxies: luminosity function,galaxy: formation,galaxy: structure},
