  abstract = {We compile observations of early-type binaries identified via spectroscopy, eclipses, long-baseline interferometry, adaptive optics, common proper motion, etc. Each observational technique is sensitive to companions across a narrow parameter space of orbital periods P and mass ratios q = \textbraceleft M\textbraceright\textbraceleft comp\textbraceright/M 1. After combining the samples from the various surveys and correcting for their respective selection effects, we find that the properties of companions to O-type and B-type main-sequence (MS) stars differ among three regimes. First, at short orbital periods P {$\lessequivlnt$} 20 days (separations a {$\lessequivlnt$} 0.4 au), the binaries have small eccentricities e {$\lessequivlnt$} 0.4, favor modest mass ratios {$<$} q{$>$} {$\approx$} 0.5, and exhibit a small excess of twins q {$>$} 0.95. Second, the companion frequency peaks at intermediate periods log P (days) {$\approx$} 3.5 (a {$\approx$} 10 au), where the binaries have mass ratios weighted toward small values q {$\approx$} 0.2-0.3 and follow a Maxwellian ``thermal'' eccentricity distribution. Finally, companions with long orbital periods log P (days) {$\approx$} 5.5-7.5 (a {$\approx$} 200-5000 au) are outer tertiary components in hierarchical triples and have a mass ratio distribution across q {$\approx$} 0.1-1.0 that is nearly consistent with random pairings drawn from the initial mass function. We discuss these companion distributions and properties in the context of binary-star formation and evolution. We also reanalyze the binary statistics of solar-type MS primaries, taking into account that 30\% \textpm{} 10\% of single-lined spectroscopic binaries likely contain white dwarf companions instead of low-mass stellar secondaries. The mean frequency of stellar companions with q {$>$} 0.1 and log P (days) {$<$} 8.0 per primary increases from 0.50 \textpm{} 0.04 for solar-type MS primaries to 2.1 \textpm{} 0.3 for O-type MS primaries. We fit joint probability density functions f(\textbraceleft M\textbraceright 1,q,P,e)\textbackslash ne f(\textbraceleft M\textbraceright 1)f(q)f(P)f(e) to the corrected distributions, which can be incorporated into binary population synthesis studies.},
  keywords = {Astrophysics - Solar and Stellar Astrophysics,binaries: close,binaries: general,stars: evolution,stars: formation,stars: massive,stars: statistics},
  annotation = {ADS Bibcode: 2017ApJS..230...15M},
  file = {/Users/daniel/Zotero/storage/BNRIJJ5S/Moe and Di Stefano - 2017 - Mind Your Ps and Qs The Interrelation between Per.pdf}
}
