  abstract = {Using the output from a grid of 60 Type II supernova models (Woosley amp; Weaver 1994) of varying mass (11 \$aprx\$ M/M\textbackslash sun \$aprx\$ 40) and metallicity (0, 10\$\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -4\textbraceright\$, 0.01, 0.1, and 1 Z\textbackslash sol), the chemical evolution of 76 stable isotopes, from hydrogen to zinc, is calculated. The chemical evolution calculation employs a simple dynamical model for the Galaxy (infall with a 4 billion year \$e\$-folding time scale onto a exponential disk and 1/r\$\textasciicircum 2\$ bulge), and standard evolution parameters, such as a Salpeter initial mass function and a quadratic Schmidt star formation rate. The theoretical results are compared in detail with observed stellar abundances in stars with metallicities in the range -3.0 \$aprx\$ [Fe/H] \$aprx\$ 0.0 dex. While our discussion focuses on the solar neighborhood where there are the most observations, the supernovae rates, an intrinsically Galactic quantity, are also discussed.},
