  abstract = {We determine the distance to the Sculptor Dwarf Spheroidal via three Population II stellar distance indicators: (a) the Tip of the Red Giant Branch (TRGB), (b) RR Lyrae variables (RRLs), and (c) the ridgeline of the blue horizontal branch (HB). High signal-to-noise, wide-field VI imaging that covers an area \$48\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash prime\textbraceright{} \textbackslash,\textbackslash times \textbackslash,48\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash prime\textbraceright{} \$ and reaches a photometric depth approximately 2 mag fainter than the HB was acquired with the Magellan-Baade 6.5 m telescope. The true modulus derived from Sculptor's TRGB is found to be \$\textbraceleft\textbackslash mu \textbraceright\_\textbraceleft o\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft TRGB\textbraceright\textbraceright =19.59\textbackslash,\textbackslash pm \textbackslash,\textbraceleft 0.07\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft stat\textbraceright\textbraceright\textbackslash,\textbackslash pm \textbackslash,\textbraceleft 0.05\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft sys\textbraceright\textbraceright\$ mag. Along with periods adopted from the literature, newly acquired RRL phase points are fit with template light curves to determine \$\textbraceleft\textbackslash mu \textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbraceleft W\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft I,V-I\textbraceright\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft RRL\textbraceright\textbraceright =19.60\textbackslash pm \textbraceleft 0.01\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft stat\textbraceright\textbraceright\textbackslash pm \textbraceleft 0.05\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft sys\textbraceright\textbraceright\$ mag. Finally, the HB distance is found to be \$\textbraceleft\textbackslash mu \textbraceright\_\textbraceleft o\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft HB\textbraceright\textbraceright\textbackslash,=19.54\textbackslash pm \textbraceleft 0.03\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft stat\textbraceright\textbraceright\textbackslash pm \textbraceleft 0.09\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft sys\textbraceright\textbraceright\$ mag. Absolute calibrations of each method are anchored by independent geometric zero-points, utilize a different class of stars, and are determined from the same photometric calibration. *Based in part on observations made with the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope, obtained at the Space Telescope Science Institute, which is operated by the Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy, Inc. under NASA contract NAS 5-26555. These observations are associated with program No. 13691. Additional observations are credited to the Observatories of the Carnegie Institution of Science for the use of Magellan-Baade IMACS.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {1284,1563,420,590,Astrophysics - Astrophysics of Galaxies,Astrophysics - Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics,Dwarf spheroidal galaxies,Galaxy distances,Population II stars,Standard candles},
