  urldate = {2026-01-10},
  abstract = {We present the discovery of three new low-latitude (\textbar b\textbar{} \textasciitilde{} 20\$\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash circ\textbraceright\$) Milky Way satellites: Yasone-1, Yasone-2, and Yasone-3. They were identified in our search for compact stellar overdensities in the Panoramic Survey Telescope and Rapid Response System 1, supported by follow-up deep photometric imaging from the Gran Telescopio Canarias OSIRIS instrument and Gaia astrometric data. These three new Milky Way satellites are found as compact stellar overdensities that exhibit structural and photometric properties consistent with old, metal-poor populations. All three are best described by isochrone fits corresponding to an age of \textasciitilde 12 Gyr and subsolar metallicities: [Fe/H] \textasciitilde{} -1.5 for Yasone-1 and Yasone-2, and [Fe/H] \textasciitilde{} -2.0 for Yasone-3. Yasone-1, located at a heliocentric distance of 12 kpc, has a physical half-light radius of 1.40 pc, an absolute V-band magnitude of +2.36, and a total stellar mass of 18.2 M\$\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot\textbraceright\$. Yasone-2, at a distance of 20 kpc, has a slightly larger size of 2.44 pc, a brighter V-band magnitude of +1.83, and a higher mass of 28.0 M\$\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot\textbraceright\$. Yasone-3, located at 15 kpc, is the faintest and least massive of the three, with M\$\_\textbraceleft V\textbraceright\$ = +2.52, a stellar mass of 14.4 M\$\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot\textbraceright\$, and a half-light radius of 2.09 pc. We also report a fourth (Yasone-4), lower-confidence hypercompact candidate located at Galactic latitude (b \textasciitilde{} 48\$\textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash circ\textbraceright\$), identified by replicating our search using the photometric catalogue of the Hyper Suprime-Cam Subaru Strategic Program Public Release. Finally, we present the discovery of sixteen (Yasone-5 to Yasone-20) new hypercompact cluster candidates in the Galactic disc. We discuss the possibility that any of the Yasone clusters may host an intermediate-mass black hole, and we advocate for follow-up spectroscopic observations to further constrain their nature.},
